<div class="pull-quote" style="border-left-color: #a8a29e; font-style: normal;">"The child supplies the power but the parents have to do the steering."<br/><span style="font-size: 0.875rem; color: #78716c;">— D.W. Winnicott</span></div>

<section id="part-one" class="reveal">
  <h2>Part One: Why the Happy Things Hurt</h2>

<p>Yaneth doesn't hate Christmas. She wants you to understand that before anything else. She buys the gifts. She makes the food. She puts the whole thing together every year with the kind of meticulous competence that belongs to people who have decided, somewhere deep and unspoken, that their children will not inherit their Decembers.</p>
<p>What she can't fully control is the week before.</p>
<p>Not the whole month — she wants to be precise about this. She functions fine. She moves through November without incident, and then, roughly seven days before Christmas, something shifts. A low-grade dread. A pulling inward. A flash of irritability that arrives without an invoice and will attach itself to the nearest available friction. Her husband has learned to read it. Her daughters know that the week before Christmas belongs to a version of their mother that requires a different kind of handling.</p>
<p>What none of them fully understand — what Yaneth herself only half-knows — is that her nervous system is doing something extremely specific in those seven days. It is counting down to a promise. And it has forty-one years of data on what promises like this tend to deliver.</p>
<p>She was four years old when her parents left Honduras.</p>

<hr/>

<p>They didn't abandon her. That distinction matters enormously to an adult reading this. To the nervous system of a four-year-old, it meant nothing. The brain at that age doesn't evaluate intent. It evaluates presence. It registers: <em>the people who are supposed to be here are not here.</em> And then it adapts.</p>
<p>Her parents left together, both at once, which meant the entire foundation lifted at once. Five children stayed behind with their maternal grandmother — a woman who raised them, and plenty of other kids besides, on barely enough of everything. The plan was a year, maybe two. They would send money, they would call, they would come back or send for the children once they'd established themselves in California. What happened instead was fifteen years.</p>
<p>The parents loved their children. The brain of a four-year-old registers none of that. It registers presence, and when presence disappears — regardless of the reason — the adaptation that follows runs on its own logic, independent of intent, for the rest of a life.</p>

<hr/>

<p>Abandonment wounds don't tend to surface in the dark moments. They surface in the ones that are supposed to be good.</p>
<p>Psychologist Ellen Hendriksen has documented what the trauma literature calls the Birthday Effect — a spike in grief, anxiety, and depression in people with abandonment histories around holidays and celebrations, entirely separate from any calendar anniversary of the original loss. The mechanism is specific, and it is not what most people assume. The brain stores painful memories with unusual fidelity as a protection system, so that sensory corridors associated with the original disappointment become alerts rather than neutral information. The smell of pine. The sound of other families' anticipation. The social architecture of a holiday that says <em>this is when the people who love you show up.</em> For someone whose nervous system learned, year after year across fifteen childhood Christmases, that the promise of the occasion wouldn't be kept — these sensory inputs now carry a threat signal. The amygdala fires. The mood drops. The countdown begins, right on schedule, seven days out.</p>
<p>What looks, from the outside, like a person who doesn't appreciate good things is a nervous system doing its job with painful precision.</p>
<p>This matters beyond Yaneth. It matters for every adult who gets inexplicably anxious before a birthday, who reliably starts a fight in the week before a family gathering, who feels a heaviness descend on the holidays that bears no relationship to anything actually happening in their present life. The research suggests they are not overreacting, not being difficult, not failing at gratitude. They are living inside a prediction their nervous system made long ago, in response to real conditions, and never updated.</p>
<p>The same system that braces for December fires in ordinary life too — in daily friction, in the moment a slight arrives that carries far more weight than it should. Yaneth's anger isn't separate from the holiday dread. It's the same alarm, in a different register.</p>
<p>In children, unprocessed grief almost always surfaces as one of two things: withdrawal or aggression. Grief is a collapse emotion — it opens, it makes the person vulnerable, it requires something from the environment to hold it. Anger is an arousal emotion — it activates, it moves outward, it has a direction and an apparent target. For a child who needed to function every day in a house where her parents weren't, grief was a liability. Anger was workable. By adulthood, the pattern is installed: the flash of heat in the chest, faster than thought, attaching itself to the nearest friction. What Yaneth experiences as a character flaw is a defense mechanism that formed before she had language, serving a purpose that no longer applies.</p>
<p>What is remarkable is how long it keeps serving. The nervous system, trained by real experience in early childhood, runs its programs with extraordinary faithfulness. By the time the adult becomes conscious enough to notice a pattern, the pattern has been running for decades.</p>
<p>There is a third expression of the same system, less obvious than the other two, and in many ways the most instructive. Yaneth is, by the account of everyone who knows her, one of the most attentive people they have ever met. She remembers two hundred birthdays. She anticipates what people need before they know they need it themselves. She absorbs other people's problems with a readiness that can look, and often feels, like pure generosity — and in large part it is. But it also runs on the same engine as the December dread and the flash of anger. The child whose nervous system learned that the important people might leave at any time becomes the adult who monitors everyone's emotional state with quiet, exhausting precision. If she can keep everyone around her satisfied, seen, cared for — no one has cause to go.</p>
<p>The clinical literature calls this anxious caregiving, and it is one of the most common and least recognized expressions of abandonment trauma in adults. What distinguishes it from ordinary generosity is the one domain it conspicuously does not cover: herself. Yaneth will carry anyone's weight. Her own she tends to set down somewhere and forget to pick back up.</p>

<hr/>

<p>Part of why the wound stays hidden so long is that it can't be narrated — and the reason is anatomy, not will or self-awareness.</p>
<p>The hippocampus — the structure responsible for building explicit, sequential memory, the kind that allows a person to say <em>at this time, in this place, this thing happened</em> — isn't fully developed until around age four or five. Which means what Yaneth retained from the morning her parents left is fragmentary at best, possibly absent entirely. She doesn't have the scene. She has the feeling the scene created: the cellular imprint of what it felt like when presence became absence, stored in the amygdala and the body, with no narrative attached to explain it.</p>
<p>The disconnect that confuses people who carry early abandonment wounds is this: the intensity of the feeling is entirely out of proportion to the thinness of the story. The feeling arrives as weather — inexplicable, internal, enormous — and when they reach for the narrative to explain it, they find almost nothing. So they conclude they're irrational. Oversensitive. Broken in some way they can't quite locate.</p>
<p>They are none of those things. They are experiencing a memory that predates their ability to form memories. The record was kept in the body because that was the only storage available.</p>

<hr/>

<p>Yaneth is forty-five years old. She has been in California for twenty-six years. She is married — twenty years to a man she describes by saying, simply, <em>I thank God he's stubborn</em> — with two daughters she is ferociously devoted to. The December bracing still comes, every year, right on schedule. Her amygdala is still running its forty-one-year program.</p>
<p>What the program is made of, and what it has cost five siblings over four decades of adult life, is what this series is about.</p>
</section>

<section id="part-two" class="reveal">
  <h2>Part Two: The Arithmetic of Absence</h2>

<p>The five siblings at the center of this story didn't turn out identically. What they turned out carrying, across four different ages and four very different adult lives, is recognizably the same thing.</p>
<p>Robert, the eldest, is the exception worth noting first. He is by every account the most social of the five — out in the world, present at gatherings, comfortable in ways his siblings find more effortful. Shy, nonetheless. The ease is partly performed, and he knows it. He was also the oldest when the parents left, which means he had banked the most attachment before the ground disappeared.</p>
<p>Ana, the second oldest, took a different route: she moved to Florida and largely got on with it, the sibling who put the most geographical distance between herself and the rest and seems, by every account, the most settled. Whether distance is the cause of that or the expression of it probably depends on what you think distance is for.</p>
<p>The others — Yaneth; Howard; and Roxanna — are described by those who know them as lovely, warm, and quietly consistent in this: given no immediate obligation, all three will retreat. To their rooms. To solitude. To spaces that make no demands and require no performance.</p>
<p>Howard's room is genuinely still — he lives with their mother in California, rarely leaves the house, brilliant and largely unreachable by the world outside it. Yaneth's retreat is the couch — severe endometriosis that puts her there for days at a stretch, and Asian dramas, which her husband has a theory about. Watching people cry all day can't be good, he reasons. But she finds it oddly settling. His best guess is that sadness is simply the emotional register she grew up inside — grief was the atmosphere of her childhood, and the dramas play in the same key. Not a wound reopening. More like the particular comfort of a room you've lived in a long time.</p>
<p>What makes the habit worth examining is that Yaneth doesn't cry at the dramas. She watches other people cry. Someone else does the weeping over loss and separation and people who left. She is present for it, soothed by it — but at one remove. Psychologists studying fictional grief have found that witnessed emotion, as distinct from felt emotion, can provide emotional proximity without the exposure that direct feeling requires. For someone whose wound predates the language to grieve it cleanly, watching others feel what she cannot quite access in herself may be the closest available approximation.</p>
<p>Roxanna's room is busy — phone in hand, tabs open, the particular industry of someone who has found that browsing requires no commitment and costs nothing and provides just enough forward motion to feel like activity without the exposure of actually beginning something. She is raising her daughter Abby, which is its own kind of anchoring, its own daily proof that showing up is possible. It is not depression, exactly, and not antisocial preference. It is the instinctive return to the only environment that early childhood taught them was entirely safe.</p>
<p>Five people, one departure. The variable across all of them is simply the age each child was when both parents disappeared — and developmental psychology is now precise enough to map what that does to a nervous system depending on when it strikes.</p>
<p>Children separated from both parents between ages three and five — Yaneth's window — tend to develop a persistent loss of security in new relationships, with the effects appearing not immediately but years later, after early childhood stress has accelerated the development of the brain's threat-detection system. The amygdala and prefrontal cortex mature faster under chronic stress, which sounds like an advantage until you understand what it produces: a threat-detection system locked to a danger level that no longer exists.</p>
<p>Children separated before age three carry a starker burden. A 2024 longitudinal study found that separation from both parents in those first years — Howard's window at two, Roxanna's at one — was associated with moderate to severe depression and impaired social functioning in adolescence and early adulthood, with severity correlating directly to the duration of the separation. Fifteen years is not a short duration.</p>

<hr/>

<p>Howard's particular expression of this — the room, the withdrawal, the brilliant man who rarely leaves the house — is consistently misread as introversion or preference. The <em>hikikomori</em> research, originating in Japan but now documented across multiple cultures, links this pattern of prolonged social withdrawal specifically to adverse childhood experiences and ambivalent early attachment. A 2023 analysis of over thirty-three thousand adults found that social isolation was associated with significantly elevated rates of major depressive disorder, social anxiety disorder, and generalized anxiety disorder. What the people who love Howard tend to describe as personality is, in clinical terms, a nervous system that was calibrated at age two to a world where the outside held catastrophic loss — and that has never been given enough evidence to think otherwise.</p>
<p>He is not isolated because he doesn't want connection. He is isolated because wanting connection and fearing it simultaneously, with no stable resolution to the tension, produces withdrawal as the only available rest.</p>

<hr/>

<p>Roxanna's relationship with starting and not finishing has its own clinical literature now, and it is worth understanding because the same pattern touches many people who would never describe themselves as traumatized.</p>
<p>A 2025 neuroimaging study used resting-state fMRI across nearly twelve hundred participants to trace the neural pathway between childhood trauma and chronic procrastination. Childhood trauma produces measurable functional alterations in the frontoparietal network, which governs cognitive control; the salience network, which determines what the brain treats as worthy of attention; and the cerebellum, which coordinates timing and the initiation of action. These alterations increase trait anxiety and reduce executive function simultaneously — a combination that makes starting, particularly on tasks involving risk or evaluation, functionally harder than it would be for someone whose brain was assembled under different conditions. A separate 2023 meta-analysis found that childhood emotional neglect was linked to a 340 percent increase in severe procrastination.</p>
<p>The gap between intention and follow-through that Roxanna lives with is not a character deficiency. It is a measurable feature of a brain shaped by an early environment it had no say in.</p>

<hr/>

<p>What unifies all five siblings — more even than the retreat to their rooms — is a shared and stubborn fear of failure: the consequence that is hardest to see from the outside and, professionally and creatively, the most quietly devastating.</p>
<p>Fear of failure, in the clinical literature, is not primarily about failure at all. It is about relationships. Researchers describe it as rooted in the anticipation of having love withdrawn when one falls short — the belief, installed early and running deep, that one's worth is contingent on performance, and that failure will confirm the original verdict: <em>not enough.</em> A 2005 study established that shame is the core emotional driver of fear of failure, and that this shame is specifically relational in origin. It is the shame of the child who concluded, in the only framework available to them, that their inadequacy was the reason the important people left — or stayed without really being present — or withheld the warmth that was supposed to be unconditional.</p>
<p>What this produces in adults is a recognizable signature: competence within established lanes, genuine resistance to new territory, an unwillingness to try things that might produce visible failure in front of other people. Not because the person lacks ambition — they often have enormous ambition — but because the cost of being seen to fall short feels, at a cellular level, existentially dangerous. Creativity requires tolerating the risk of being wrong. Exploration requires the capacity to survive disapproval. When your foundational architecture encodes the message <em>I was not enough to make them stay</em>, any situation that might confirm that verdict becomes a threat rather than a challenge.</p>
<p>This pattern, crucially, transmits. Elliot and Thrash documented in 2004 that fear of failure passes from parent to child through modeling and conditional regard — through children watching adults treat risk as dangerous, and through love and approval felt as contingent on achievement. The grandmother who raised these five on barely enough, in a country that was hard, had her own relationship to failure. It would have been remarkable if she hadn't passed some version of it forward.</p>

<hr/>

<p>The body runs its own accounting alongside all of this, quietly.</p>
<p>Research using biomarkers finds that adults with childhood abandonment histories demonstrate altered immune functioning, increased inflammatory response, and disrupted cortisol regulation — changes that help explain elevated rates of autoimmune disorders, chronic pain, and stress-related illness in this population. The HPA axis, the body's cortisol production system, is calibrated in early childhood by the emotional environment the child inhabits. In an environment defined by unpredictability and attachment needs that were chronically unmet, it learns a single lesson and runs it faithfully: <em>stay ready.</em> Forty-one years of elevated baseline cortisol is not metaphor. It is inflammatory markers, cardiovascular wear, an immune function that has been running in low-grade crisis since the Reagan administration.</p>
<p>Yaneth's endometriosis is severe enough to be disabling on its worst days. The research on the link between chronic inflammatory conditions and early trauma is not yet definitive, but it is consistent enough to constitute a pattern worth noting: the body that spent decades in low-grade cortisol elevation is a body that tends toward inflammation, toward autoimmune activity, toward the particular category of conditions in which the immune system — trained for perpetual readiness — turns its vigilance inward.</p>
<p>The CDC and Kaiser Permanente's Adverse Childhood Experiences study — tracking over seventeen thousand adults across multiple health domains — found that adults reporting four or more adverse childhood experiences were three times more likely to abuse alcohol. Substance use is frequently where the body's unresolved distress surfaces most visibly: neurochemically, alcohol and other substances quiet the amygdala and produce, temporarily, the experience of safety that the body never learned to generate on its own. The problem is not that the solution works. It is that it works just enough.</p>

<hr/>

<p>The accumulated weight of all this — the braced Decembers, the rooms, the unfinished things, the five adults who won't try new things if they can help it — has a name that the clinical literature arrived at relatively recently. Pauline Boss, a researcher at the University of Minnesota, coined the term <em>ambiguous loss</em> to describe losses that lack the cultural acknowledgment and closure rituals that allow people to grieve. A death has a funeral. A divorce has legal finality and social permission to be devastated. Ambiguous loss has neither.</p>
<p>Parents who migrate and leave children behind are physically absent but psychologically present — on the phone, sending money, the subject of a reunion that keeps receding into the future. The child cannot grieve cleanly because the object of the grief is still alive, still calling, still planning the return. So the grief goes sideways. It becomes the bracing before celebrations. The rage with nowhere clean to land. The retreat to the room. The five adults who are lovely and capable and quietly convinced — somewhere below conscious thought — that they were not enough, and that this was why. A verdict that was never actually handed down. One that a four-year-old, left without explanation, reached for anyway.</p>
<p>You cannot hold someone who is not there. You carry the idea of them instead, and the idea is always larger than the person would have been.</p>
</section>

<section id="part-three" class="reveal">
  <h2>Part Three: The People Who Stay</h2>

<p>Yaneth was nineteen and doing well — college, a boyfriend, something that felt like the beginning of contentment — when her mother called from California.</p>
<p>That she was doing well matters. The cultural script around immigration stories insists on the reunion as resolution: the family becomes whole, everyone exhales, the hardship was worth it. What the script omits is that the call at nineteen was not a reunion. Her parents never came back to Honduras. They didn't arrive at the grandmother's door, road-worn and older, to hold the children they'd left. What happened was a phone call that said, in essence: <em>we're ready for you now. Come to us.</em></p>
<p>Which meant Yaneth would have to do the crossing. She would have to leave the grandmother who had actually raised her — the woman around whom her entire attachment structure had been organized for fifteen years. The boyfriend. The college enrollment. The country. The self she had assembled, carefully and without parental guidance, over fifteen years of being essentially on her own.</p>
<p>She went. She arrived in California. She walked into a house where two people who were factually her parents were experientially strangers, and was expected to love them with a fluency that fifteen years of absence had made impossible. That particular rupture — the child's long-constructed idea of who her parents are meeting two tired, complicated people who rebuilt their lives without her — is rarely discussed in the immigration literature, which tends to count the reunion as the end of the story.</p>

<hr/>

<p>The research on abandonment trauma and early romantic attachment is specific enough to be almost predictive. People with anxious-preoccupied attachment styles — the most common adult outcome of early abandonment — tend to fast-track intimacy, to move toward warmth quickly and with the urgency of something that has been waiting a long time. The nervous system that spent fifteen years being trained on absence experiences the sudden presence of someone attentive as profound relief, and reaches for it before the slower, more deliberate parts of the mind have caught up.</p>
<p>Yaneth got pregnant at twenty-one. She married the father — they tried, recognized quickly that trying wasn't enough, and ended it without cruelty. At twenty-three, she met the man she has been married to since 2006. She arrived in that relationship with Michelle, who was two and a half years old — still in the window when a child's nervous system is actively deciding what adults do, and whether they can be trusted to stay.</p>
<p>What Yaneth gave her daughter, from the beginning, was the specific and unacademic understanding of someone who had been exactly Michelle's age when her own world went quiet.</p>

<hr/>

<p>What followed is described in the attachment literature as earned secure attachment — a concept that is well-supported by research and, outside clinical circles, almost entirely unknown.</p>
<p>The conventional understanding of attachment theory — that the patterns formed in early childhood tend to persist — is true as far as it goes. What it doesn't account for is neuroplasticity, and specifically the documented phenomenon of adults with insecure attachment histories developing genuinely secure attachment through sustained experience of a reliable, responsive relationship. Neurologically genuine security — the kind that shows up in clinical interviews as a coherent, integrated account of one's past, without the anxiety or avoidance that signal an unresolved wound — not the performance of stability, but the real thing.</p>
<p>Research shows that insecure attachers can develop healthier, more secure relationships through sustained healthy bonds, and that people with earned security go on to function in relationships similarly to those who had secure attachment from the start. The key word is <em>sustained.</em> The nervous system that built its working model on the evidence of fifteen years does not update on the basis of a pleasant first date. It updates over time, through the slow accumulation of counter-evidence sufficient to revise a prediction it has been running since childhood.</p>

<hr/>

<p>Yaneth calls her husband stubborn, which in this context is the highest available praise. What the anxious-preoccupied nervous system does, when it finds someone who might be safe, is test them — not consciously, not always fairly, with the full accumulated force of everything it learned about what people do when things get hard. Twenty years in, they are, as he puts it, both screwed up in their own ways but oddly perfect for each other — and they know they love each other deeply. The December bracing still comes. The amygdala still fires its forty-one-year program. But it no longer runs the household.</p>

<hr/>

<p>Michelle is twenty-four. She has been raised, from her earliest clear memories, by a woman who understood what it costs a child to feel unprotected and was constitutionally unable to allow it on her watch. Michelle's father became a friend — birthdays and holidays spent together, the kind of extended family assembled through choice rather than biology. Michelle grows up watching the adults in her life refuse the standard script: that endings are ruptures, that love is finite, that occasions meant to celebrate belonging are better approached with armor.</p>
<p>Isabelle is nineteen — the same age Yaneth was when the call came from California. She has never known a household without both her parents in it. She is nineteen in a way that Yaneth, at nineteen, was not: unencumbered by fifteen years of ambiguous grief, free to make the mistakes that nineteen-year-olds are supposed to make without the existential weight of survival underneath them.</p>

<hr/>

<p>For the siblings who haven't found their own version of this — and for the considerably larger world of adults who will recognize something of themselves in this story — the clinical treatment research points somewhere real.</p>
<p>EMDR works not by helping people talk about the past but by helping the brain reprocess traumatic memories, moving them from the hyperactivated limbic system into the integrated regions where they can be understood as past rather than present. For traumas that predate coherent language, this non-narrative mechanism is particularly relevant — and its effects extend well beyond the classic symptoms. In controlled research, trauma-focused therapy decreased chronic procrastination by 62 percent over eight weeks, compared to 11 percent for conventional cognitive-behavioral therapy, which points to something important: the behaviors this series has described — the avoidance, the unfinished things, the retreat from risk — are not habits that respond to habit-change strategies. They are trauma responses, and they yield to trauma treatment. Dialectical Behavior Therapy builds precisely the skills the wound erodes: emotional regulation, distress tolerance, the capacity to communicate needs without either demanding or suppressing them. Somatic experiencing addresses the body-stored component directly — the cortisol dysregulation, the amygdala that can't be argued down — because the nervous system doesn't update through insight alone. It updates through physical experience of safety, accumulated over time. All of it is available to people who are forty-five, or sixty-five, or anywhere between.</p>

<hr/>

<p>One thread in this story rarely gets its due in the clinical literature.</p>
<p>The grandmother. The woman who raised five children for fifteen years on barely enough of everything, who was a grandmother and not a parent and could not be a parent and was asked to be one anyway. Every day of her consistent, present, imperfect love was a day in which the nervous system's core prediction — <em>no one stays</em> — was quietly disconfirmed. She gave these five children thousands of those days. She didn't fix what the leaving made. But she gave their brains enough counter-evidence that the wound, however deep, did not become entirely defining.</p>
<p>She doesn't appear in the clinical literature. She was just a woman who stayed.</p>

<hr/>

<p>Yaneth's parents left Honduras because they loved their children. That is true, and it is the whole of their defense, and it is sufficient.</p>
<p>Yaneth's children will never have to wonder if their parents are coming back. That is also true.</p>
<p>The distance between those two truths is fifteen years long. It is the length of a childhood, the width of an ocean, and the entire subject of this series. What the research cannot quite capture is what Yaneth herself has spent forty-one years slowly, imperfectly, genuinely learning: that the people who were supposed to stay and didn't were not a verdict on her worth. That the record kept in the body can be revised. That the December countdown, which has run since she was four, runs now against a counterweight she built herself — one relationship, one household, one Christmas at a time.</p>

<p><em>The siblings' names have been changed. Their stories are told with their knowledge and in gratitude for their willingness to be known.</em></p>
